According to a report by Intel Market Research, the global furfurylamine market was valued at USD 23.2 million in 2024 and is projected to grow from USD 24.4 million in 2025 to USD 34.3 million by 2032, registering a CAGR of 5.2% during the forecast period. The market is witnessing steady expansion as industries increasingly adopt bio-based chemical intermediates for pharmaceutical manufacturing, agrochemicals, specialty chemicals, and advanced materials. Produced from renewable agricultural by-products such as corncobs, sugarcane bagasse, and other biomass resources, furfurylamine is emerging as a sustainable alternative to petroleum-derived chemicals, supporting the global shift toward green chemistry and environmentally responsible industrial production.
